\begin_layout Section*
Selim
\end_layout

\begin_layout Section*
Development Accounting
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection*
The Aggregate Technology
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
We start by assuming that the technology to produce aggregate output is
 given by
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
Y_{i}=A_{i}K_{i}^{\alpha_{i}}\left(avh_{i}\cdot h_{i}\cdot L_{i}\right)^{(1-\alpha_{i})},
\]

\end_inset

where
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula $Y_{i}:$
\end_inset

 real GDP in country 
\begin_inset Formula $i$
\end_inset

, measured at PPP
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula $A_{i}:$
\end_inset

total factor productivity in country 
\begin_inset Formula $i$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula $K_{i}:$
\end_inset

real physical capital in country 
\begin_inset Formula $i$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula $h_{i}:$
\end_inset

average human capital per worker in country 
\begin_inset Formula $i$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula $avh_{i}:$
\end_inset

average hours worked per worker in country 
\begin_inset Formula $i$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula $L_{i}:$
\end_inset

labour force in country 
\begin_inset Formula $i$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection*
Measuring Standards of Living
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
There are a few alternative to measuring standards of living.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
A first approach focuses on the most widely used measure of standards of
 living, output per capita
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\frac{Y_{i}}{N_{i}}=A_{i}\left(\frac{K_{i}}{N_{i}}\right)^{\alpha_{i}}\left(avh_{i}\cdot h_{i}\cdot\frac{L_{i}}{N_{i}}\right)^{(1-\alpha_{i})}
\]

\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula 
\[
y_{i}=A_{i}\left(k_{i}\right)^{\alpha_{i}}\left(avh_{i}\cdot h_{i}\right)^{(1-\alpha_{i})}\left(\frac{L_{i}}{N_{i}}\right)^{(1-\alpha_{i})}
\]

\end_inset

Under this approach, differences in standards of living are driven by gaps
 in total factor productivity 
\begin_inset Formula $A_{i}$
\end_inset

, in capital per capita 
\begin_inset Formula $\alpha_{i}$
\end_inset

, in average hours worked per capita 
\begin_inset Formula $avh_{i},$
\end_inset

in average human capital per capita 
\begin_inset Formula $h_{i},$
\end_inset

and in the employment to population ration 
\begin_inset Formula $\frac{L_{i}}{N_{i}}.$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
A second approach re-arranges the production function to express output
 per-capita (or per-worker) as a function of country 
\begin_inset Formula $i's$
\end_inset

 capital-output ratio.
 Starting with 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\frac{Y_{i}}{N_{i}}=A_{i}\left(\frac{K_{i}}{N_{i}}\right)^{\alpha_{i}}\left(\frac{avh_{i}\cdot h_{i}\cdot L_{i}}{N_{i}}\right)^{(1-\alpha_{i})},
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
and multiplying and divide the right hand side by 
\begin_inset Formula $\left(\frac{Y_{i}}{N_{i}}\right)^{\alpha_{i}}$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\left(\frac{Y_{i}}{N_{i}}\right)=A_{i}\left(\frac{K_{i}}{N_{i}}\frac{N_{i}}{Y_{i}}\right)^{\alpha_{i}}\left(\frac{avh_{i}\cdot h_{i}\cdot L_{i}}{N_{i}}\right)^{(1-\alpha_{i})}\left(\frac{Y_{i}}{N_{i}}\right)^{\alpha_{i}},
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\left(\frac{Y_{i}}{N_{i}}\right)=A_{i}^{\left(\frac{1}{1-\alpha_{i}}\right)}\left(\frac{K_{i}}{Y_{i}}\right)^{\left(\frac{\alpha_{i}}{1-\alpha_{i}}\right)}\left(\frac{avh_{i}\cdot h_{i}\cdot L_{i}}{N_{i}}\right),
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
we obtain that 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
y_{i}=A_{i}^{\left(\frac{1}{1-\alpha_{i}}\right)}\left(\frac{K_{i}}{Y_{i}}\right)^{\left(\frac{\alpha_{i}}{1-\alpha_{i}}\right)}\left(avh_{i}\cdot h_{i}\right)\left(\frac{L_{i}}{N_{i}}\right).
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Note that the second approach is equivalent to the first approach, so both
 should yield the same results.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
A third approach focuses on differences in GDP per worker.
 To be precise
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\frac{Y_{i}}{L_{i}}=A_{i}\left(\frac{K_{i}}{L_{i}}\right)^{\alpha_{i}}\left(avh_{i}\cdot h_{i}\right)^{(1-\alpha_{i})},
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
y_{i}^{pw}=A_{i}\left(k_{i}^{pw}\right)^{\alpha_{i}}\left(avh_{i}\cdot h_{i}\right)^{(1-\alpha_{i})}.
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Naturally, this last equation can be re-aranged so as to express differences
 in income per-worker as a function of the capital-output ratio as well.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection*
Implementation
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Continue here.
 The idea is that we take logs, normalize the US to 1, and express differences
 in standards of living relative to the US.
 Gaps with the US will be given by gaps in TFP and factors, conditional
 on alphas being the same.
 The next step is to perform a variance (in logs) decomposition to see the
 shares of diferences in standards of living that can be accounted for by
 factors.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Inputs for this section: we want to have charts of the normalized variables
 like in Hsieh and Klenow (AEJ Macro,2010).
 On the x axis we want to show GDP per capital at PPP relative to the US,
 and in the Y axis capital per worker, average hours, average human capital,
 labour force to population ratios, and capital output ratios.
 We also want to have (a sorted table) with the countries in our sample.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
A potential concern is that our results are driven by sample selection.
 Here we want to do two robustness checks.
 First, try to create an indiator variable for the countries in Caselli's
 sample, and redo de analysis for those countries only.
 Another concern is that we cut our sample too short, because the goal was
 to have a sample of countries with observations for all variables.
 I think the limiting variable here is 
\begin_inset Formula $avh$
\end_inset

 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection*
Variance Decomposition
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Let the per-worker production function be
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
y=Ak^{\alpha}\left(avh\cdot h\right)^{(1-\alpha)},
\]

\end_inset

and define 
\begin_inset Formula $y_{hk}$
\end_inset

 as the output that is purely prodcuced by factors.
 To be precise
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
y_{hk}=k^{\alpha}\left(avh\cdot h\right)^{(1-\alpha)}.
\]

\end_inset

It follows that
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
y=Ay_{hk},
\]

\end_inset

and
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
log\left(y\right)=log\left(A\right)+log\left(y_{hk}\right),
\]

\end_inset

with
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
log\left(y_{hk}\right)=\alpha log\left(k\right)+(1-\alpha)log\left(avh\cdot h\right)
\]

\end_inset

To perform an exact variance decomposition in closed form, we proceed as
 follows:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
Compute 
\begin_inset Formula $var\left(log(y)\right).$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
Fix the value of 
\begin_inset Formula $\alpha$
\end_inset

 at 
\begin_inset Formula $\bar{\alpha}=1/3$
\end_inset

 (or the mean/median of the sample) and compute 
\begin_inset Formula $var\left(\left.log(y)\right|\alpha=\bar{\alpha}\right).$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
Define 
\begin_inset Formula $var\left(log(\tilde{y})\right)=var\left(\left.log(y)\right|\alpha=\bar{\alpha}\right).$
\end_inset

Decompose 
\begin_inset Formula $var\left(log(\tilde{y})\right).$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
It follows that
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
log\left(\tilde{y}\right)=log\left(A\right)+log\left(\tilde{y}_{hk}\right)
\]

\end_inset

Applying the variance operator on both sides, we obtain
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
var\left(log(\tilde{y})\right)=var\left(log(A)\right)+var\left(log(\tilde{y}_{hk})\right)+cov\left(log(A),log(\tilde{y}_{hk})\right).
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
The second term is:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
var\left(log(\tilde{y}_{hk})\right)=\bar{\alpha}^{2}var\left(log(k)\right)+(1-\bar{\alpha})^{2}var\left(log(avh\cdot h)\right)+2\bar{\alpha}(1-\bar{\alpha})cov\left(log(k),log(avh\cdot h)\right)
\]

\end_inset

Decomposing the last two terms
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
var\left(log(avh\cdot h)\right) & =var\left(log(avh)+log(h)\right)\\
 & =var\left(log(avh)\right)+var\left(log(h)\right)+2cov\left(log(avh),log(h)\right)
\end{align*}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
cov\left(log(k),log(avh\cdot h)\right) & =cov\left(log(k),log(avh)+log(h)\right)\\
 & =cov\left(log(k),log(avh)\right)+cov\left(log(k),log(h)\right)
\end{align*}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
var\left(log(\tilde{y}_{hk})\right) & =\bar{\alpha}^{2}var\left(log(k)\right)+(1-\bar{\alpha})^{2}var\left(log(avh\cdot h)\right)+2\bar{\alpha}(1-\bar{\alpha})cov\left(log(k),log(avh\cdot h)\right)\\
 & =\bar{\alpha}^{2}var\left(log(k)\right)+(1-\bar{\alpha})^{2}var\left(log(avh\cdot h)\right)+2\bar{\alpha}(1-\bar{\alpha})cov\left(log(k),log(avh\cdot h)\right)
\end{align*}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\]

\end_inset

The remaining covariance is just 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
cov\left(log(A),log(\tilde{y}_{hk})\right) & =cov\left(log(A),\alpha log\left(k\right)+(1-\alpha)log(avh)+(1-\alpha)log(h)\right)\\
 & =\bar{\alpha}cov\left(log(A),log(k)\right)+(1-\bar{\alpha})cov\left(log(A),log(avh)\right)+(1-\bar{\alpha})cov\left(log(A),log(h)\right)
\end{align*}

\end_inset


\begin_inset Newline newline
\end_inset

It follows that
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
var\left(log(\tilde{y})\right) & =var\left(log(A)\right)+\bar{\alpha}^{2}var\left(log(k)\right)+(1-\bar{\alpha})^{2}var\left(log(avh)\right)+(1-\bar{\alpha})^{2}var\left(log(h)\right)\\
 & +2(1-\bar{\alpha})^{2}cov\left(log(avh),log(h)\right)\\
 & +2\bar{\alpha}(1-\bar{\alpha})cov\left(log(k),log(avh)\right)+2\bar{\alpha}(1-\bar{\alpha})cov\left(log(k),log(h)\right)\\
 & +\bar{\alpha}cov\left(log(A),log(k)\right)+(1-\bar{\alpha})cov\left(log(A),log(avh)\right)+(1-\bar{\alpha})cov\left(log(A),log(h)\right)
\end{align*}

\end_inset


\end_layout

